We can split the quality into 2 separate groups: less than 5.5 and more than 5.5

Then, we can create boxplots again to see if there is any different between < 5.5 and > 5.5 quality

In [47]:
data_less = data[data['quality'] < 5.5].drop('quality', axis=1).copy()
data_more = data[data['quality'] > 5.5].drop('quality', axis=1).copy()
In [48]:
n=1

columns = data.columns[:-1]
less_q = []
more_q = []

for col in columns:
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))
    ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, n)
    sns.boxplot(data=data_less, y=col)
    plt.title(f'{col} (quality < 5.5) \n mean = {round(data_less[col].mean(), 3)} \n std = {round(data_less[col].std(), 3)}')
    
    ax2 = plt.subplot(1, 2, n+1, sharey=ax1)
    sns.boxplot(data=data_more, y=col, color='orange')
    plt.ylabel('')
    plt.title(f'{col} (quality > 5.5) \n mean = {round(data_more[col].mean(), 3)} \n std = {round(data_more[col].std(), 3)}')
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.2, hspace=0.3)
    n = 1
    
    diff = data_less[col].mean() - data_more[col].mean()
    if diff > 0:
        less_q.append((col, round(abs(diff)*100/data_less[col].mean(), 3)))
    elif diff < 0:
        more_q.append((col, round(abs(diff)*100/data_more[col].mean(), 3)))
    

    plt.show()

from scipy.stats import norm, skew, boxcox
for i in skews:
    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.distplot(data[i], fit = norm, color=wine_colors[0])
    plt.title('Skeweed')
    plt.show()
    (mu, sigma) = norm.fit(data[i])
    print("mu {} : {}, sigma {} : {}".format(i, mu, i, sigma))
    print()
    
    data[i], lam = boxcox(data[i])

    sns.set_style('whitegrid')
    sns.distplot(data[i], fit = norm, color=wine_colors[1])
    plt.title('Transformed')
    plt.show()
    (mu, sigma) = norm.fit(data[i])
    print("mu {} : {}, sigma {} : {}".format(i, mu, i, sigma))
    print()

k = []
l = []
for i in range(1,250):
    rf_tune = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=i)
    rf_tune.fit(x_train,y_train)
    y_pred = rf_tune.predict(x_test)
    k.append(float(accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)*100))
    l.append(i)
    
k = pd.DataFrame(k , columns=['Accuracy']) 
l = pd.DataFrame(l , columns=['n_estimator'])
df = pd.concat([k, l], axis = 1)
